My data set is from Kaggle and contains information about packages. The target is whether or not the package was received on time. A 1 means the the package was not received on time, and a 0 means that it was.

Data Transformations

Things to consider:

  • split multi-attribute categories
  • bin/discretize numeric data
  • remove attributes
  • scaling
  • missing values
  • nominal to numeric
  • feature importance
  • redundant attributes
shipping = read.csv(file = '~/School Work/SP21/Data Mining - CS 346/shipping.csv')

There are no missing values in the data.

Split categorical values into numerical

shipping_new = dummy_cols(shipping, select_columns = c("Warehouse_block", "Mode_of_Shipment", "Product_importance", "Gender"))


shipping_new = shipping_new %>% 
    select(-c("Warehouse_block", "Mode_of_Shipment", "Product_importance", "Gender", "ï..ID"))

shipping = shipping %>% 
    select(-"ï..ID")

shipping$Reached.on.Time_Y.N = as.factor(shipping$Reached.on.Time_Y.N)

shipping_new$Reached.on.Time_Y.N = as.factor(shipping_new$Reached.on.Time_Y.N)

The variables ‘Warehouse_block’, ‘Mode_of_Shipment’, ‘Product_importance’, and ‘Gender’ were categorical variables that needed to be split into 0/1 numerical values to use certain models. I also changed the target column to be a factor in this step.

Remove Attributes

After transforming the columns, I removed the original columns from the data. I also removed the ‘id’ column since it was not useful for the analysis.

Scaling

In order to use SVM and neural nets, the numerical values need to be scaled. I scaled ‘Customer_care_calls’, ‘Customer_rating’, ‘Cost_of_the_Product’, ‘Prior_purchases’, ‘Discount_offered’, and ‘Weight_in_gms’.

normalize <- function(x) {
return ((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))
}

shipping_new$Customer_care_calls = normalize(shipping_new$Customer_care_calls)
shipping_new$Customer_rating = normalize(shipping_new$Customer_rating)
shipping_new$Cost_of_the_Product = normalize(shipping_new$Cost_of_the_Product)
shipping_new$Prior_purchases = normalize(shipping_new$Prior_purchases)
shipping_new$Discount_offered = normalize(shipping_new$Discount_offered)
shipping_new$Weight_in_gms = normalize(shipping_new$Weight_in_gms)

Redundant Attributes

I don’t think there are any redundant columns in the data

I also don’t think there are any nominal attributes.

Testing Data on a Decision Tree

Before doing any of the more complicated models, I ran a simple decision tree with my data. For the decision tree I used the version of my data set with no scaled values and the categorical values, since a decision tree does not require scaled numeric data. I split my data into a training and testing set before running.

require(caTools)
sample = sample.split(shipping, SplitRatio = .75)
train = subset(shipping, sample == TRUE)
test  = subset(shipping, sample == FALSE)

train$Reached.on.Time_Y.N = as.factor(train$Reached.on.Time_Y.N)
test$Reached.on.Time_Y.N = as.factor(test$Reached.on.Time_Y.N)
set.seed(5)
fit <- rpart(Reached.on.Time_Y.N ~ .,
             method="class", data=train)

printcp(fit) # display the results

After generating predictions using my test set and creating a confusion matrix, we can see that the decision tree was 68% accurate. The main reason for doing a decision tree was to see if the data would work when using modeling techniques and to be able to run feature importance.

Feature Importance from Decision Tree

imp = varImp(fit, scale = FALSE)
imp
plot(imp)

Most important variables: - Discount offered (828.33) - Weight in grams (610.5) - Prior purchases (103.02) - Cost of product (69.59) - Customer care calls (44.3)

Not important: - Customer rating & Mode of shipment (1.7) - Warehouse block, Product importance, & gender (0)

Random Forest on All Variables

The first more advanced model I ran was a random forest. I ran the random forest on all of the variables in the data using the original version of the data since a random forest can handle categorical and unscaled data. I used the same training and testing data that I created when running the decision tree.

set.seed(5)
rf <- randomForest(
  Reached.on.Time_Y.N ~ .,
  data=train
)

rf
##

##  randomForest(formula = Reached.on.Time_Y.N ~ ., data = train)

accuracy_Test <- sum(diag(cm)) / sum(cm)

## [1] 0.6673333

The random forest is around 67% accurate when using the training data to generate predictions. This is slightly less accurate than the decision tree.

Neural Net

The next model I did was a Neural Net. Neural nets use scaled numeric data, so I used the version of the data set that I did data transformations on to generate my training and testing sets.

set.seed(5)

shipping_new$Reached.on.Time_Y.N = as.factor(shipping_new$Reached.on.Time_Y.N)
sample = sample.split(shipping_new, SplitRatio = .75)
NNtrain = subset(shipping_new, sample == TRUE)
NNtest  = subset(shipping_new, sample == FALSE)

I intended to build a few different neural nets to compare. The first one was predicting Reached on time from two features, Weight in grams and Discount offered. These were the two most important features to both the decision tree and the random forest. This ANN has one hidden layer with 3 nodes, and uses the logistic activation function.

  1. Weight in grams & Discount offered
NN = neuralnet(Reached.on.Time_Y.N ~ Weight_in_gms + Discount_offered, NNtrain, hidden = 3, act.fct = "logistic", linear.output = F)

# plot neural network
plot(NN)
predict_testNN = compute(NN, NNtest[,-7]) 

prob = predict_testNN$net.result 

pred <- ifelse(prob[,2]>0.5, 1, 0)

predFactor <- as.factor(pred)

confusionMatrix(predFactor,NNtest$Reached.on.Time_Y.N)

SVM

For SVM, I am using the same training and testing sets as in the neural net because SVM requires numeric, scaled data.

  1. SVM with all features
classifier = svm(formula = Reached.on.Time_Y.N ~ .,
                 data = NNtrain,
                 type = 'C-classification',
                 kernel = 'linear')

# plot

plot(classifier, NNtest,  Weight_in_gms ~ Discount_offered)

# Predicting the Test set results
y_pred = predict(classifier, newdata = NNtest[-7])

# Making the Confusion Matrix
cm = table(NNtest[, 7], y_pred)

accuracy_Test <- sum(diag(cm)) / sum(cm)
accuracy_Test
## [1] 0.6653328

A SVM with all of the features is around 66% accurate.

  1. SVM with 2 most important features - Weight in grams and Discount offered
classifier = svm(formula = Reached.on.Time_Y.N ~  Weight_in_gms + Discount_offered,
                 data = NNtrain,
                 type = 'C-classification',
                 kernel = 'linear')

## plot

plot(classifier, NNtest,  Weight_in_gms ~ Discount_offered)

# Predicting the Test set results
y_pred = predict(classifier, newdata = NNtest[-7])

# Making the Confusion Matrix
cm = table(NNtest[, 7], y_pred)

accuracy_Test <- sum(diag(cm)) / sum(cm)
accuracy_Test
## [1] 0.6606039

SVM with the two most important features is around 66% accurate.

Looking at all of the models and their accuracy, they are all fairly close to each other around 66% accurate. The most accurate model with the ANN with the 3 most important features, which was around 70% accurate.
